        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">From Mr. C. Darwin</hi>. [Bassett, Southampton.]</placeName>
                    <date>May 8<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>                   
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>Thanks for another &amp; much better lot of specimens of the Ledum.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I doubt whether case worth labour of investigation. The glands probably serve, in accordance with Kerner’s view, merely to protect the flowers from crawling insects, which would not cross-fertilise them.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>C.D.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 <hi rend="italic">Mr. C. Darwin</hi>] ‘<hi rend="italic">Mr.</hi>’ <hi rend="italic">altered from</hi> ‘<hi rend="italic">Mrs.</hi>’; <hi rend="italic">before del</hi> ‘<hi rend="italic">Down, Beckenham, Kent.</hi>’ </note>
            </div>
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11494.xml">letter from T. H. Farrer, 4 May 1878</ref>. </note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11494.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from T. H. Farrer, 4 May 1878</ref> and n. 1. CD initially thought the plant would be worth investigating to determine whether it was insectivorous (<ref target="./DCP-LETT-11495.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to T. H. Farrer, 7 May [1878]</ref>). The genus <hi rend="italic">Ledum</hi> has been subsumed within the genus <hi rend="italic">Rhododendron</hi>; leaves of many species of <hi rend="italic">Ledum</hi> have insecticidal properties.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Anton Kerner had mentioned that access to the flowers of <hi rend="italic">Ledum palustre</hi> was impeded by sticky secretions from the epidermis of the bracts (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10293.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Kerner 1876</ref>, p. 215). </note>
        </div>   
       
